## Next Research Directions

- Test each pair in the mapping for non-trivial correspondence: do physicalism and anatta share characteristic internal tensions (e.g., both struggle to account for why the illusion of consciousness or self is so persistent and functionally consequential), or does the parallel hold only at the coarsest logical level?
- Investigate whether the devotional response (consciousness known through love and participation) has genuine analogues in philosophy of mind: Levinas on ethics-as-first-philosophy, Buber on I-Thou, certain readings of Whitehead's process philosophy. If it does, the gap closes and the topology is more complete than the model claims. If it does not, the gap is evidence of a systematic observational bias in the field.
- Apply the topology to a specific test case: take the debate over vegetative state and minimally conscious patients, where the question of whether phenomenal experience is present drives clinical and ethical decisions. Do the available positions (it is present, it is absent, it seems present but is not, it is present but unknowable, the question is ill-formed) map onto the six-fold topology? If they do, the model has predictive reach beyond the general hard problem.
- Run the same mapping with a non-reflexive domain such as free will and check whether an identical topology appears. If it does, reflexivity is not the cause of the limited menu; logical option space is. If the topology differs in non-reflexive domains, the reflexive bind is genuinely doing explanatory work that the catuskoti alone cannot explain.
- Protocol improvement: after using any negation-based contemplative method as a thinking lens, check whether the felt remainder pressure is a structural product of the negation method rather than a feature of the object being investigated. The neti neti lens builds remainder pressure by design; a lens that does not negate (devotion, situational attunement, aesthetic perception) might encounter consciousness without generating the hard problem at all, which would mean the hard problem is partly an artifact of the analytic stance, not a permanent feature of consciousness.

